14. Types of Blockchain
1.	Public Blockchain
o	Open to everyone
o	Example: Bitcoin, Ethereum, Litecoin, Dash
2.	Private Blockchain
o	Controlled by a single organization
3.	Permissioned Blockchain
o	Restricted access
o	Example: Hyperledger
4.	Hybrid / Consortium Blockchain
o	Combination of public and private features
________________________________________
15. Public Blockchain ‚Äì Key Points
‚Ä¢	Transactions and data are publicly visible
‚Ä¢	Participant identities can remain anonymous
‚Ä¢	Fully decentralized
________________________________________
Litecoin
‚Ä¢	Litecoin is a forked version of Bitcoin
‚Ä¢	Uses similar blockchain principles but with faster transaction confirmation
________________________________________
16. Types of Blockchain
16.1 Private Blockchain
Definition:
A blockchain where access and control are restricted to a single organization.
Characteristics:
1.	Transactions are secret and visible only to the administrator
2.	All participants are known
3.	Controlled by a single organization
________________________________________
16.2 Permissioned Blockchain
Definition:
A blockchain where participants require permission to join and perform actions.
Characteristics:
1.	Transactions are semi-secret
2.	Visible only to specific members
3.	Participant identities are linked to real-world identities
Examples:
‚Ä¢	Hyperledger
‚Ä¢	R3 Corda
‚Ä¢	Ripple (used for fastest financial transactions)
________________________________________
17. Blockchain Types Comparison
Feature	Public Blockchain	Private Blockchain	Permissioned Blockchain
Consensus Determination	All participating nodes	Only admin	Authorized members
Data Access	Public	Restricted	Restricted to certain degree
Immutability	Almost impossible to tamper	Can be mutated	Can be mutated
Resource Requirement	Low	High	High
Centralization	No	Yes	Semi-centralized
Permission Required	No	Yes	Yes
________________________________________
