21. Cryptographic Keys
Types of Keys
1.	Public Key
2.	Private Key
________________________________________
Public Key
‚Ä¢	Publicly available cryptographic key
‚Ä¢	Used by anyone to send encrypted messages
‚Ä¢	Only the holder of the corresponding private key can decrypt the message
________________________________________
Private Key
‚Ä¢	Highly secure, randomly generated value
‚Ä¢	Kept secret by the owner
‚Ä¢	Used to decrypt data and sign transactions
‚Ä¢	Must never be shared
________________________________________
22. Cryptographic Categories
22.1 Symmetric Cryptography
Definition:
Uses the same key for encryption and decryption
Also known as Shared Key Cryptography
Flow Diagram:
Sender ‚Üí Encrypt (Key) ‚Üí Cipher Text ‚Üí Decrypt (Same Key) ‚Üí Receiver
Ciphertext:
Encrypted message using symmetric key
________________________________________
22.2 Asymmetric Cryptography
Definition:
Encryption key is different from decryption key
Also known as Public Key Cryptography

Flow Diagram:
Sender ‚Üí Encrypt (Receiver‚Äôs Public Key) ‚Üí Cipher Text  ‚Üí Decrypt (Receiver‚Äôs Private Key) ‚Üí Receiver
________________________________________
23. Message Signing (Digital Signature)
Purpose:
Used to verify integrity and authenticity of message
Flow Diagram:
Sender ‚Üí Sign (Sender‚Äôs Private Key)  ‚Üí Signature ‚Üí Verify (Sender‚Äôs Public Key) 	   ‚Üí Receiver
________________________________________
Key Usage Summary
Operation	Key Used
Encryption	Receiver‚Äôs Public Key
Decryption	Receiver‚Äôs Private Key
Signing	Sender‚Äôs Private Key
Verification	Sender‚Äôs Public Key
________________________________________
24. Hash Function
Definition:
A mathematical function that converts input data of arbitrary length into a fixed-length output
Properties:
‚Ä¢	Same input ‚Üí Same hash
‚Ä¢	Small change in input ‚Üí Completely different hash
‚Ä¢	Impossible to derive input from hash
Examples:
‚Ä¢	MD5
‚Ä¢	SHA-1
‚Ä¢	SHA-2
‚Ä¢	SHA-3
‚Ä¢	RIPEMD
‚Ä¢	Whirlpool
Example:
hello ‚Üí hash(hello) ‚Üí AAF4C6...
________________________________________
25. Merkle Tree
Definition:
A data structure used to summarize and verify integrity of large data sets
Also known as Binary Hash Tree
Structure (Text Diagram):
            Root Hash (Merkle Root)
            	 /              \
       	 Hash PQ              Hash RS
       	 /     \             	         /      \
     Hash P  Hash Q       Hash R   Hash S
         |     	|                  |            |
    Tran P    Tran Q        Tran R   Tran S
________________________________________
Advantages of Merkle Tree
1.	Ensures data integrity
2.	Less memory requirement
3.	Fast and easy computation
4.	Efficient data validation
5.	Less information transfer required
________________________________________
26. Proof of Work (PoW)
Definition:
A consensus algorithm used to confirm transactions and produce new blocks
Characteristics:
‚Ä¢	Miners compete to solve cryptographic puzzles
‚Ä¢	Uses complex mathematical problems
‚Ä¢	First miner to solve gets reward
‚Ä¢	Widely used in Bitcoin
________________________________________
